00:39:24.486 --> 00:39:27.830
AUDIENCE: So one of the things
that always interests me is

00:39:27.830 --> 00:39:31.350
keeping users motivated,
particularly in algorithms

00:39:31.350 --> 00:39:33.370
wrapping a human into it.

00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:35.610
What are some of the ways that
you've seen that people are

00:39:35.610 --> 00:39:39.060
using motivational systems to
keep users engaged for long

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:42.080
terms without any kind of cliff
at the end, where they

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:44.530
just lose interest and stop
playing the game?

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:48.010
GABE ZICHERMANN: So it's not
possible to design an

00:39:48.010 --> 00:39:55.080
experience that is a perpetual
motion machine for engagement.

00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:59.140
We don't have the ability to
write one set of code that

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:04.380
will forever be interesting to
people, because one of the

00:40:04.380 --> 00:40:05.670
characteristics of people--

00:40:05.670 --> 00:40:07.920
not even this new generation
of consumer that I've been

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:09.510
talking, but all people--

00:40:09.510 --> 00:40:13.490
is that we quickly habituate
to stimuli.

00:40:13.490 --> 00:40:16.610
So just so that we could put the
science into context, it

00:40:16.610 --> 00:40:17.430
just came out.

00:40:17.430 --> 00:40:20.400
The research was published
recently, I think, in

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:23.910
"Science." And they wrote it up
in the "New York Times." So

00:40:23.910 --> 00:40:26.800
they said that the average
romantic relationship between

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:33.650
people spend two years in a
state of romantic affection.

00:40:33.650 --> 00:40:36.300
And then after about two years,
switches to become

00:40:36.300 --> 00:40:38.280
companionship affection.

00:40:38.280 --> 00:40:41.900
So we stop waking up every day
going, oh my god, my partner's

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:45.190
so amazing and start waking up
every day and going, OK, we

00:40:45.190 --> 00:40:47.830
got to take the kids
to school.

00:40:47.830 --> 00:40:49.780
I'm glad this person is here.

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:51.430
So romance shifts to
companionship.

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:55.310
Now, many couples when they
encounter that transition,

00:40:55.310 --> 00:40:57.080
they feel badly about
themselves.

00:40:57.080 --> 00:40:59.570
Because they're like, I somehow
failed in this.

00:40:59.570 --> 00:41:02.560
My relationship is no longer as
hot and fresh and exciting

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:04.090
as it was before.

00:41:04.090 --> 00:41:07.070
The science behind that
is called habituation.

00:41:07.070 --> 00:41:10.520
And all of your human senses,
your brain is wired to

00:41:10.520 --> 00:41:13.430
eventually habituate to stimuli,
that is to say, to

00:41:13.430 --> 00:41:15.630
normalize stimuli.

00:41:15.630 --> 00:41:18.160
Think about why that's important
evolutionarily.

00:41:18.160 --> 00:41:21.500
Like a really bad smell, if you
didn't habituate to it,

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:24.380
but it was perpetual,
you'd go crazy.

00:41:24.380 --> 00:41:27.640
Background noise, if you don't
learn habituate to that kind

00:41:27.640 --> 00:41:29.240
of background noise,
you'd go crazy.

00:41:29.240 --> 00:41:33.780
Right now, if a caveman was
unfrozen and became a lawyer

00:41:33.780 --> 00:41:37.630
and showed up here,
they would note--

00:41:37.630 --> 00:41:39.120
It's an SNL joke.

00:41:39.120 --> 00:41:43.030
They would note that there was a
loud hum in the room, like a

00:41:43.030 --> 00:41:45.290
very loud machine hum,
because they've

00:41:45.290 --> 00:41:46.440
never heard that before.

00:41:46.440 --> 00:41:48.360
We don't hear it anymore,
because we've

00:41:48.360 --> 00:41:49.160
habituated to it.

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:51.900
But it's all around
you all the time.

00:41:51.900 --> 00:41:56.550
So habituation is the enemy of
long term engagement design.

00:41:56.550 --> 00:41:58.930
Every time a stimulus is
presented and is presented

00:41:58.930 --> 00:42:01.120
over and over again, eventually
people become

00:42:01.120 --> 00:42:01.900
immune to it.

00:42:01.900 --> 00:42:05.320
One technique is to do what's
called operant conditioning,

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:08.410
which is slot machine effect.

00:42:08.410 --> 00:42:12.580
If you can never predict the
reward, ever, in any way, and

00:42:12.580 --> 00:42:16.010
you can't predict its timing or
its size or its frequency,

00:42:16.010 --> 00:42:18.830
then in theory, you'll be
forever pressing a pedal

00:42:18.830 --> 00:42:20.790
trying to get that
thing to happen.

00:42:20.790 --> 00:42:25.500
But people even find
that disturbing.

00:42:25.500 --> 00:42:28.880
So the key is whatever you're
going to do to design long

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:31.380
term engagement for users
requires you to design it in

00:42:31.380 --> 00:42:32.490
the long term.

00:42:32.490 --> 00:42:34.980
Design it early, middle,
and late game.

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:36.360
Continue to invest in it.

00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:38.800
Continue to evolve
it over time.

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:40.810
They're clearly some games like
Nike+ which continue to

00:42:40.810 --> 00:42:43.360
be played over the long term.
"World of Warcraft" is played

00:42:43.360 --> 00:42:44.370
over the long term.

00:42:44.370 --> 00:42:46.290
But make no mistake
that those are

00:42:46.290 --> 00:42:47.990
continuously being expanded.

00:42:47.990 --> 00:42:50.030
Those are continuously
being evolved.

00:42:50.030 --> 00:42:52.046
They're always being changed
and updated.

