Because baseball's
kind of slow.

00:47:35.530 --> 00:47:35.990
GABE ZICHERMANN: It
is kind of slow.

00:47:35.990 --> 00:47:38.000
AUDIENCE: It's a one person
kind of thing.

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:41.710
And when we play this game, it's
like they're so active.

00:47:41.710 --> 00:47:42.940
And they're cheering
on each other.

00:47:42.940 --> 00:47:45.090
But in the game, you're
kind of, you know--

00:47:45.090 --> 00:47:47.740
GABE ZICHERMANN: So there's a
lot of interesting research on

00:47:47.740 --> 00:47:50.700
how to design feedback loops
for optimal outcomes.

00:47:50.700 --> 00:47:54.140
And there's no clear answer
for how to do that.

00:47:54.140 --> 00:47:59.450
There's not one ring to rule
them all when it comes to how

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:02.983
to design a feedback loop.

00:48:02.983 --> 00:48:04.050
AUDIENCE: One of the
question is--

00:48:04.050 --> 00:48:07.265
So we're getting the feedback
in the game practicing.

00:48:07.265 --> 00:48:11.020
But in the actual, when we
want them to perform--

00:48:11.020 --> 00:48:13.410
GABE ZICHERMANN: What's the
purpose of a practice game?

00:48:13.410 --> 00:48:14.965
AUDIENCE: Oh, it's not
a practice game.

00:48:14.965 --> 00:48:17.510
It's just this, for
the ground balls.

00:48:17.510 --> 00:48:18.640
They line up.

00:48:18.640 --> 00:48:19.660
And we throw ground
balls to them.

00:48:19.660 --> 00:48:20.560
They get points.

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:22.000
GABE ZICHERMANN: Why?

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:23.513
AUDIENCE: They find it fun.

00:48:23.513 --> 00:48:25.430
GABE ZICHERMANN: Are you doing
it because they find it fun or

00:48:25.430 --> 00:48:27.190
are you doing it because
that will improve their

00:48:27.190 --> 00:48:27.475
performance?

00:48:27.475 --> 00:48:28.940
AUDIENCE: We want them to
improve their performance in

00:48:28.940 --> 00:48:29.570
the actual game.

00:48:29.570 --> 00:48:30.200
GABE ZICHERMANN: OK.

00:48:30.200 --> 00:48:32.500
AUDIENCE: So I wonder, like
in the game, it's so slow.

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:34.510
In the actual game, it's so
slow, they might not even get

00:48:34.510 --> 00:48:36.280
the chance to actually
catch a ground ball.

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:38.490
GABE ZICHERMANN: Right?

00:48:38.490 --> 00:48:42.610
AUDIENCE: They perform lower
in the real situation.

00:48:42.610 --> 00:48:44.640
GABE ZICHERMANN: So a
couple quick things.

00:48:44.640 --> 00:48:47.950
One is, if you're going to
design a proxy experience for

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:50.900
people, so you let's say you
were designing a simulator to

00:48:50.900 --> 00:48:53.020
simulate being a pilot.

00:48:53.020 --> 00:48:55.340
Many of you have seen
those aircraft

00:48:55.340 --> 00:48:56.820
simulators on TV or movies.

00:48:56.820 --> 00:48:58.060
Some of you have probably
been in one.

00:48:58.060 --> 00:48:59.080
It's kind of awesome.

00:48:59.080 --> 00:49:01.530
I really want to go in one.

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:04.620
So that simulator has to
be super realistic.

00:49:04.620 --> 00:49:07.745
That simulator cannot be
partially realistic.

00:49:07.745 --> 00:49:10.700
It can't suffer from, what's
called the uncanny valley,

00:49:10.700 --> 00:49:14.060
which some of you might know
from game design, where you

00:49:14.060 --> 00:49:17.770
get something that looks and
feels a lot like reality, but

00:49:17.770 --> 00:49:18.890
then isn't reality.

00:49:18.890 --> 00:49:21.510
So you sit there spending a lot
of your energy figuring

00:49:21.510 --> 00:49:23.840
out, is it real or isn't it,
instead of just being in the

00:49:23.840 --> 00:49:26.210
experience, or constantly
being pulled in and out.

00:49:26.210 --> 00:49:29.200
If you build a simulator to
simulate the experiences that

00:49:29.200 --> 00:49:31.560
somebody's supposed to have in
real life and that simulator

00:49:31.560 --> 00:49:34.815
is better than real life, why do
you think that people would

00:49:34.815 --> 00:49:37.380
want to do the thing in real
life, as much as they would

00:49:37.380 --> 00:49:39.760
want to do the simulator?

00:49:39.760 --> 00:49:42.630
So that's a genuine issue.

00:49:42.630 --> 00:49:45.880
It's similar to the nuclear
plant manager thought example

00:49:45.880 --> 00:49:50.760
that I gave you earlier, which
is you do this exciting

00:49:50.760 --> 00:49:51.660
training thing.

00:49:51.660 --> 00:49:53.110
And the actual thing
a sort of boring.

00:49:53.110 --> 00:49:56.730
So one piece of advice
I would give is, make

00:49:56.730 --> 00:49:57.640
baseball more exciting.

00:49:57.640 --> 00:50:01.230
We could all benefit from that,
if that's within your

00:50:01.230 --> 00:50:02.770
power to do.

00:50:02.770 --> 00:50:06.600
If it's not within your power
to do, I would look for ways

00:50:06.600 --> 00:50:11.460
to make that simulation more
like actual baseball and maybe

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:15.200
put people on different tracks
depending on their actual

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:16.110
skill level.

00:50:16.110 --> 00:50:19.030
So if they are more highly
skilled and more highly

00:50:19.030 --> 00:50:24.620
motivated, maybe they will be
fine doing the high speed

00:50:24.620 --> 00:50:27.710
practice, because they're being
driven to play that

00:50:27.710 --> 00:50:31.900
other game a different way
versus your average player or

00:50:31.900 --> 00:50:34.920
below average player, for whom
as soon as the attention

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:35.900
shifts out of the--

00:50:35.900 --> 00:50:38.770
They drop out of attention,
they're not going to be

00:50:38.770 --> 00:50:41.310
engaged anymore.

00:50:41.310 --> 00:50:44.190
I'd like to see your new
baseball, Baseball 2.0.

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:46.566
I might even play it.

00:50:46.566 --> 00:50:47.340
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:48.716
GABE ZICHERMANN: Thank you.

00:50:48.716 --> 00:50:51.360
AUDIENCE: In terms of enterprise
gamification, what

00:50:51.360 --> 00:50:53.850
are the most common stumbling
blocks you've seen, maybe in

00:50:53.850 --> 00:50:57.295
your consulting work, where
do things go wrong or

00:50:57.295 --> 00:51:00.450
where do they fail?

00:51:00.450 --> 00:51:02.270
GABE ZICHERMANN: So the biggest
mistake that companies

00:51:02.270 --> 00:51:04.220
make all the time, this
happens all the time.

00:51:04.220 --> 00:51:06.440
So it's like a company will be
like, alright well, we, want

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:08.540
to gamify an employee
interaction, because we're

00:51:08.540 --> 00:51:13.790
trying to improve throughput,
improve outcomes, whatever.

00:51:13.790 --> 00:51:16.750
So my first question to them is
always, how are you going

00:51:16.750 --> 00:51:18.750
to get them to use it?

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:22.660
Because 4/5 of enterprise
software implementations fail,

00:51:22.660 --> 00:51:24.100
more or less.

00:51:24.100 --> 00:51:26.100
So how are you going to get
people to use this thing?

00:51:26.100 --> 00:51:30.530
And typically, especially if
it's HR driven, the company

00:51:30.530 --> 00:51:34.480
will say, well, they're
going to have to do.

00:51:34.480 --> 00:51:38.500
So by Fiat, that's the method
for delivering new software.

00:51:38.500 --> 00:51:41.120
And the truth is, people don't
like being told what to do.

00:51:41.120 --> 00:51:43.850
It doesn't matter how
fun the game is.

00:51:43.850 --> 00:51:47.120
If I preface my gamify solution
by saying, you must

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:51.200
play this game, you're probably
going to be like, no,

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:52.450
not so much.

00:51:54.580 --> 00:51:56.450
So that's a really
big mistake.

00:51:56.450 --> 00:52:00.520
We have to make enterprise
engagement design to the same

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:02.210
standards as consumer
engagement.

00:52:02.210 --> 00:52:04.020
You'd never try to get
your customers to do

00:52:04.020 --> 00:52:05.170
something like that.

00:52:05.170 --> 00:52:07.330
Why get your employees to
do something like that?

00:52:07.330 --> 00:52:10.030
And the more we start to
realize, and I talk about this

00:52:10.030 --> 00:52:13.830
in the evolution of this
consumer point, that same

00:52:13.830 --> 00:52:17.510
person who's just as distracted
by their smartphone

00:52:17.510 --> 00:52:20.690
at home, who can't watch--

00:52:20.690 --> 00:52:21.560
Crazy stat.

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:26.020
The last month, 80% of the
American population has

00:52:26.020 --> 00:52:30.990
watched television with a second
or third screen open

00:52:30.990 --> 00:52:32.850
while watching.

00:52:32.850 --> 00:52:37.530
Now, it wasn't that long ago
that TV was the distraction.

00:52:37.530 --> 00:52:40.930
And now, we need a distraction
from the distraction just to

00:52:40.930 --> 00:52:43.230
feel like our brains
are functioning.

00:52:43.230 --> 00:52:45.000
Are you frustrated at the movies
when you go that you

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:46.160
can't open your phone?

00:52:46.160 --> 00:52:46.520
I am.

00:52:46.520 --> 00:52:47.390
I think about it all the time.

00:52:47.390 --> 00:52:49.750
It's like, I want to do
something, but I have to just

00:52:49.750 --> 00:52:50.900
watch this movie.

00:52:50.900 --> 00:52:59.150
And so set against that
backdrop, why would employees

00:52:59.150 --> 00:53:01.880
suddenly not become normal
humans when they walk through

00:53:01.880 --> 00:53:03.880
the door at work?

00:53:03.880 --> 00:53:06.170
What is it about the walking
through the doorway at the

00:53:06.170 --> 00:53:10.050
office that suddenly makes
them not distracted, that

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:12.030
suddenly makes the not
hedonistic, that suddenly

00:53:12.030 --> 00:53:14.950
makes them not want to follow
feedback, friends, and fun?

00:53:14.950 --> 00:53:18.130
Nothing, p.s.

00:53:18.130 --> 00:53:20.950
Historically, we've
depended on this.

00:53:20.950 --> 00:53:26.280
We've all been part of this
shared delusion that the

00:53:26.280 --> 00:53:28.410
office is somehow not
like the free market

00:53:28.410 --> 00:53:29.890
for people's attention.

00:53:29.890 --> 00:53:32.490
And in practice, it's
no different.

00:53:32.490 --> 00:53:34.890
So to build successful
enterprise gamification, you

00:53:34.890 --> 00:53:37.110
have to start thinking about
your employees as consumers,

00:53:37.110 --> 00:53:39.470
think about them in the same
context as consumers, and

00:53:39.470 --> 00:53:42.620
design that experience with
that same idea in mind.

00:53:42.620 --> 00:53:44.010
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:53:44.010 --> 00:53:46.910
My question is, can you use
gamification to actually

00:53:46.910 --> 00:53:50.950
reduce engagement, like to
addictions or products like

00:53:50.950 --> 00:53:52.386
that, which you actually
would like to--

00:53:52.386 --> 00:53:52.790
GABE ZICHERMANN: Yes.

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:56.210
In fact, two of the most
successful examples of

00:53:56.210 --> 00:54:00.510
gamification are Alcoholics
Anonymous and Weight Watchers,

00:54:00.510 --> 00:54:02.610
both of which are behavior
cessation games.

00:54:02.610 --> 00:54:04.960
And in fact, Weight Watchers
employs a fair number of game

00:54:04.960 --> 00:54:06.880
designers to tweak
the design of it.

00:54:06.880 --> 00:54:09.770
And they're two of the most
successful behavior cessation

00:54:09.770 --> 00:54:11.410
systems in the world.

00:54:11.410 --> 00:54:16.490
They have many of the same core
design principles of the

00:54:16.490 --> 00:54:18.160
other gamified examples that
we've talked about.

00:54:18.160 --> 00:54:19.350
So they've got points.

00:54:19.350 --> 00:54:20.330
And they've got badges.

00:54:20.330 --> 00:54:21.190
And they have levels.

00:54:21.190 --> 00:54:22.440
And they've got achievements
and some

00:54:22.440 --> 00:54:24.730
degree of leader boards.

00:54:24.730 --> 00:54:26.250
So they've got all
the mechanics.

00:54:26.250 --> 00:54:30.260
But what makes them especially
powerful is that they're all

00:54:30.260 --> 00:54:33.730
about helping people
achieve mastery.

00:54:33.730 --> 00:54:36.960
And any time you design your
experience, something

00:54:36.960 --> 00:54:39.220
gamified, we spend a lot of
time talking about helping

00:54:39.220 --> 00:54:42.430
people achieve mastery, how
gamification drives mastery.

00:54:42.430 --> 00:54:45.120
And the more you're able to
drive mastery in people, the

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:48.790
more loyalty they give you,
the more control they give

00:54:48.790 --> 00:54:51.510
you, the more confidence they
impart in your system.

00:54:51.510 --> 00:54:57.830
So basically, if you give
somebody the mastery over

00:54:57.830 --> 00:54:59.610
something that they want
to control, they're

00:54:59.610 --> 00:55:01.820
loyal to you forever.

00:55:01.820 --> 00:55:03.100
So consider this.

00:55:03.100 --> 00:55:04.740
You run into somebody
on the street.

00:55:04.740 --> 00:55:06.900
You haven't seen them
in five years.

00:55:06.900 --> 00:55:09.490
You're like, oh my god,
you look amazing.

00:55:09.490 --> 00:55:10.450
You've lost so much weight.

00:55:10.450 --> 00:55:12.300
You look amazing.

00:55:12.300 --> 00:55:14.280
They turn to you and they're
like, oh yeah, I did it at

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:16.520
Weight Watchers.

00:55:16.520 --> 00:55:17.060
How'd you do it?

00:55:17.060 --> 00:55:18.050
Weight Watchers.

00:55:18.050 --> 00:55:19.810
But it's not Weight Watchers.

00:55:19.810 --> 00:55:22.500
You actually had to do
diet and exercise.

00:55:22.500 --> 00:55:24.550
The person did the work.

00:55:24.550 --> 00:55:27.250
They did the work, the same work
that everybody else does.

00:55:27.250 --> 00:55:30.310
They just used Weight Watchers
as the system to do it.

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:33.620
When the system delivers
mastery, people will replace

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:36.430
their sense of self
accomplishment with the system

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:37.860
as the identity.

00:55:37.860 --> 00:55:39.770
They do that all the time.

00:55:39.770 --> 00:55:42.260
That's its kind of
loyalty side.

00:55:42.260 --> 00:55:45.460
So you can change behavior when
people want to change

00:55:45.460 --> 00:55:48.610
their behavior by using
those systems.

00:55:48.610 --> 00:55:52.190
If your question was whether,
can you force people to change

00:55:52.190 --> 00:55:53.910
their behavior?

00:55:53.910 --> 00:55:55.200
It depends on whether
or not you believe

00:55:55.200 --> 00:55:58.010
people have free will.

00:55:58.010 --> 00:56:00.410
If you believe they have free
will, then you cannot force

00:56:00.410 --> 00:56:02.500
them to do anything.

00:56:02.500 --> 00:56:06.720
If you don't believe they have
free will, then you can

00:56:06.720 --> 00:56:08.600
certainly force them to
do certain things.

00:56:08.600 --> 00:56:10.910
AUDIENCE: So seguing from
addiction, all of these seem

00:56:10.910 --> 00:56:15.460
to be about moving people who
aren't already addicted to

00:56:15.460 --> 00:56:17.650
gamification process
into this process.

00:56:17.650 --> 00:56:20.640
What do you do when people's
limited engagement is maxed

00:56:20.640 --> 00:56:23.810
out on all these things
we've built, these

00:56:23.810 --> 00:56:24.730
feedback cycles for--

00:56:24.730 --> 00:56:28.650
Like, how do you make them do
Foldit instead of more cow

00:56:28.650 --> 00:56:31.005
tipping on Facebook?

00:56:31.005 --> 00:56:34.450
GABE ZICHERMANN: Well, I think
it's just an arms race.

00:56:34.450 --> 00:56:38.520
So just like everything else
that you have to do, any other

00:56:38.520 --> 00:56:41.420
kind of behavior change or user
engagement system, over

00:56:41.420 --> 00:56:42.800
time they lose their efficacy.

00:56:42.800 --> 00:56:46.360
And you have to overcome
their habituation.

00:56:46.360 --> 00:56:49.160
Thankfully today, the market
is more wide open than you

00:56:49.160 --> 00:56:49.590
would think.

00:56:49.590 --> 00:56:53.990
Even in writing "Gamification
Revolution," where we were

00:56:53.990 --> 00:56:55.490
researching and looking at
these companies that were

00:56:55.490 --> 00:56:57.420
really doing this strategically,
that were

00:56:57.420 --> 00:57:00.920
really crushing the competition
with gamification,

00:57:00.920 --> 00:57:02.680
there's not that
many examples.

00:57:02.680 --> 00:57:05.910
It's like we had 500 examples
to choose from.

00:57:05.910 --> 00:57:07.350
We didn't have that many
where they're really

00:57:07.350 --> 00:57:09.360
doing it that well.

00:57:09.360 --> 00:57:11.670
So one of the things about
gamification is it's a

00:57:11.670 --> 00:57:14.390
relatively new trend with
pretty deep roots.

00:57:14.390 --> 00:57:16.280
And because we're in the tech
business, we've heard the term

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:17.050
for three years.

00:57:17.050 --> 00:57:19.140
And we're like, oh everyone's
doing it.

00:57:19.140 --> 00:57:21.760
But look around Google.

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:23.790
How much of it is actually
being done?

00:57:23.790 --> 00:57:26.560
Some of it is like conceptual
people want to do it.

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:28.900
Sometimes we dipped our toe
in the water somewhere.

00:57:28.900 --> 00:57:30.810
But not that many companies are
actually doing it doing

00:57:30.810 --> 00:57:33.700
it, deliberately doing
it, purposefully.

00:57:33.700 --> 00:57:36.890
So the market is still fairly
open in most categories.

00:57:36.890 --> 00:57:39.530
And I would say even in
categories where gamification

00:57:39.530 --> 00:57:41.240
has been particularly
successful, like

00:57:41.240 --> 00:57:42.780
the wellness category--

00:57:42.780 --> 00:57:47.070
I challenge you to find a
wellness startup in the last

00:57:47.070 --> 00:57:48.450
two years that isn't a

00:57:48.450 --> 00:57:50.520
gamification-based wellness startup.

00:57:50.520 --> 00:57:52.980
It's hard to find one.

00:57:52.980 --> 00:57:56.440
Even in the wellness category
like the best performer, Nike+

00:57:56.440 --> 00:57:59.640
arguably, or RunKeeper or
Fitbit, one of those, none of

00:57:59.640 --> 00:58:01.802
them are A plusses.

00:58:01.802 --> 00:58:04.020
Not to be critical, but none of
them have knocked it out of

00:58:04.020 --> 00:58:05.000
the ballpark.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.360
Nike+ is great, but it's
5 million people.

00:58:07.360 --> 00:58:08.870
But it's 5 million people.

00:58:08.870 --> 00:58:11.430
It's not 500 million people.

00:58:11.430 --> 00:58:13.110
So we still have work to do.

00:58:13.110 --> 00:58:15.510
We've still got a
long way to go.

00:58:15.510 --> 00:58:17.700
I won't stand up here
and tell you that I

00:58:17.700 --> 00:58:20.790
have all the answers.

00:58:20.790 --> 00:58:24.460
What I have is clarity that
there's a real challenge.

00:58:24.460 --> 00:58:27.480
And it's going to require the
effort of all people doing

00:58:27.480 --> 00:58:30.090
whatever it is that they're
doing to lean into actually

00:58:30.090 --> 00:58:31.340
make that a reality.

00:58:34.340 --> 00:58:36.160
Thanks to you.

00:58:36.160 --> 00:58:37.100
Awesome.

00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:37.950
Thank you so much.

00:58:37.950 --> 00:58:42.030
And if you're a Twitter person,
you can chat with me

00:58:42.030 --> 00:58:42.560
on Twitter.

00:58:42.560 --> 00:58:43.910
I'm @gzicherm.

00:58:43.910 --> 00:58:44.560
Thank you everybody.

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:45.020
I really appreciate it.

00:58:45.020 --> 00:58:46.270
Thank you.

